(y')^2 = 2 (1-\cos(y))
y
x
y(x) \to 0
x \to -\infty
y(x) \to 2\pi
x \to +\infty
2 y''(x) y'(x) = 2 y'(x) \sin y(x)
y''(x) = \sin y(x)
y(x)=\pi - \theta(x)
\theta''(x) = -\sin \theta(x)
\lim\limits_{x\to-\infty} \theta(x) = \pi
\lim\limits_{x\to+\infty} \theta(x) = -\pi
1-\cos y=1-(\cos^2\frac y2-\sin^2\frac y2)=2\sin^2\frac y2
1-\cos(y) = 2 \sin^2 \left( \frac{y}{2} \right)
y'^2 = 4 \sin^2 \left( \frac{y}{2} \right) \implies y' = \pm 2 \sin \left( \frac{y}{2} \right)
